I came over the makelab flyer in the kit going through the papers again this morning and as we do a lot of 3dp I was curious as to what they would charge for any of our items. So I opened an account and uploaded one of the frame parts and well its now analyzing the part for 9 hours. So I uploaded another one on a different computer and that is analyzing for 5 hours now. So I figure I ask here if anyone has used them and if they are any good. Btw we printed all those parts and each one prints in less time than the analyzing takes. Ideally it would be nice to be able to get something printed reasonably and quickly if one is in a pinch. But reasonably is probably out.

Comments welcome

Here is my take on it - don’t do it.

1.) They said upload “Cad files” so I uploaded the ipt from inventor. Instead of saying “file type not supported” or something like that it just hankgs.

2.) So I uploaded the STL. and clicked PETG. No setting regarding how much infill you want or how solid or optimize for strength etc it is The model might print with a .4 nozzle with 2 walls and break the first time you put some load on it

3.) on my printer it uses 440 g of PETG which I buy in quantity for about $12/kg (50kg at a time) and that is printed solid (100% infill). So about $5 in material. The quote is $250. The part prints on my K1Max with a .4 in about 10 hours. So they charge you at least 25 bucks a print hour. So for an FRC team with lots of 3dp to do not economically feasable

So at least for us its not a useful source especially as there does not seem any control over the quality (infill etc) of the print. It might be useful if you want to print a small thing you might want to hang on the wall or hand to a sponsor etc and are willing to pay plenty of $$$. Otherwise… Well you can buy a K1 max between $700 and 900 or an equivalent printer (this will also print on an ender. You can get the filament and teach some kids how to print it and after the 4th piece (we use 4 of those. you are financially ahead of the game
